  "prompt": "Why does I feel like I'm being watched whenever I go out?",
  "response": "Feeling like you're being watched can stem from several factors, including:\n\n1. **Social Anxiety**: If you tend to feel anxious in social situations, you might be more aware of others' gazes or perceive them as judging you.\n\n2. **Self-Consciousness**: Being overly aware of your appearance or actions can lead to the sensation that others are watching you closely.\n\n3. **Past Experiences**: If you've had experiences where you felt scrutinized or judged, those feelings might resurface in similar situations.\n\n4. **Hypervigilance**: This can occur due to stress or anxiety, leading you to be more alert to your surroundings and the behavior of others.\n\n5. **Intuition**: Sometimes, we pick up on social cues or body language that suggest someone is observing us, even if it\u2019s not as pronounced as we think.\n\n6. **Paranoia**: In some cases, the feeling may stem from deeper psychological issues, where the perception of being watched is more pronounced.\n\nIf this feeling is distressing or persistent, it might be helpful to talk to a mental health professional who can provide support and strategies to manage it.",
